Great question — this is a classic gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, a new DI scope is created automatically per HTTP request, so `AddScoped<MyDbContext>()` gives you a fresh `DbContext` for each request.

**In MAUI, there is no per-request scope.** The app has a single root scope for its entire lifetime. This means `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton` — your `DbContext` lives as long as the app does, accumulating tracked entities and returning stale data.

### Fixes

**Option 1 — Use `AddTransient`:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();
```
Each injection gets a new instance. Simple, but you lose the ability to share a context within a single logical operation.

**Option 2 — Use `IServiceScopeFactory` to create explicit scopes:**
```csharp
// Registration
builder.Services.AddScoped<MyDbContext>();

// In your page/viewmodel
public class MyViewModel
{
    private readonly IServiceScopeFactory _scopeFactory;

    public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)
        => _scopeFactory = scopeFactory;

    public async Task LoadDataAsync()
    {
        using var scope = _scopeFactory.CreateScope();
        var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
        // db is scoped to this block and disposed at the end
    }
}
```

**Option 2 is the recommended pattern** — it mirrors the per-request behavior you're used to and ensures the `DbContext` is properly disposed after each unit of work.
